Cultured from lab air in Weill Hall on a rose bengal plate. Soft green color, white around edges, distinct aspergillus conidiophores, uniseriate phialides suggest fumigatus. Quickly spread over plate.
Collected from the air in my apartment (yikes!). The unique black spores and filamentous body helped identify this species.
iNaturalist suggests this is the Aspergillus niger.

Under the microscope, I saw that they balled up, which ruled out penicillium, another common fungi found in American kitchens. I then cross referenced images of different species of Aspergillus and found my culture looked the most like the Aspergillus niger cultured on other malt plates.

You can see the conidial heads of the conidiophores, characters of ascomycota. The images look almost exactly like the microscopic images of aspergillus niger I saw online, taken at 10X and 40X. It was a contaminant on my plate originally meant for a chytrid, but it is a common airborne fungi in the area.
Isolated from a plate unsuccessfully attempting to culture powdery mildew on a fallen leaf. Black color and radiate, globose conidial heads led to ID.

This is a mold. ID to species. It is a common contaminant of food, as it causes the desease 'black mold' on certain fruits and vegetables, such as grapes, apricots, onions, peanuts etc. It is a strict aerobe. It is classified as safe for use in food production, although it is capable of producing toxins that affect human health.

occurrenceRemarks: Philalides and conidia cover entire vesicle (not A. Fumigatus).

This specimen was isolated from an air culture. An RBA plate was left open in a kitchen in Berkeley, CA for an hour. I then further isolated the specimen and grew it on a PDA plate. Aspergillus forms spores in the form of conidia which are found commonly in air and around food. Considering the sample was taken from kitchen air, this makes sense. Furthermore, Aspergillus has hyphae with septae which is shown in the microscopic images above. Due to the unique morphology, we can further specify what species of fungus this sample is. Aspergillus niger is one of the most common species of Aspergillus. It also has a very distinct macroscopic morphology. It is brown in color and looks dirt-like, as shown in the first picture. The microscopic morphology is also unique. The conidiophores are biseriate and this species as a radiating conidiophore head (meaning the conidia radiate all the way around the vesicle). This is depicted in pictures 2 and 3.
The conidiophores resemble closely to what Aspergillus looks like under the microscope, a long stipe and a ball of multiple small black spores (similar to a basketball shape) on the top of the stipe.
